SIMPLE: living
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Living
<hw>Liv"ing</hw> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧v"⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From
<er>Live</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Being alive;
having life; <as>as, a <ex>living</ex> creature</as>. Opposed to
<ant>dead</ant>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Active; lively; vigorous; -- said esp. of states of
the mind, and sometimes of abstract things; <as>as, a <ex>living</ex>
faith; a <ex>living</ex> principle.</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧ <xex>Living</xex>
hope. ⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Wyclif.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Issuing continually from the earth; running;
flowing; <as>as, a <ex>living</ex> spring</as>; -- opposed to
<ant>stagnant</ant>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Producing life, action, animation, or vigor;
quickening.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Living</xex> light.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Ignited; glowing with heat; burning; live.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then on the <qex>living</qex> coals wine they pour.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Living force</b></col>. <cd>See <cref>Vis viva</cref>,
under <er>Vis</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Living gale</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a heavy gale.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Living
rock</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Living stone</b></col></mcol>,
<cd>rock in its native or original state or location; rock not
quarried.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧ I now found myself on a rude and narrow stairway,
the steps of which were cut out of the <xex>living rock</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Moore.</au> -- <col><b>The living</b></col>, <cd>those who are
alive, or one who is alive.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Living</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Living
<hw>Liv"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The state of one who,
or that which, lives; lives; life; existence.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Health and
<xex>living</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Manner of life; <as>as, riotous <ex>living</ex>;
penurious <ex>living</ex>; earnest <ex>living</ex>.</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧ A
vicious <xex>living</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Means of subsistence; sustenance; estate; <as>as, to
make a comfortable <ex>living</ex> from writing</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She can spin for her <qex>living</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He divided unto them his <qex>living</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Luke xv.
12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Power of continuing life; the act of living, or
living comfortably.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is no <qex>living</qex> without trusting somebody or other
in some cases.</q> <rj><qau>L' Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The benefice of a clergyman; an ecclesiastical
charge which a minister receives.</def> <mark>[Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He could not get a deanery, a prebend, or even a
<qex>living</qex></q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Livingly</ent>⟦br⟧
